## Diagnosis

The nav logo "Yilan Gao" is wrapping because the flex container is allowing the logo text node to shrink or break across lines under viewport pressure. The surrounding flex layout is likely distributing space without explicit protection for the identity-critical element.

**Anti-pattern: AP-072** — Unprotected identity elements in responsive flex containers. Core brand/identity nodes participate in the same shrink/grow negotiation as secondary content, causing them to collapse under pressure.

---

## Root Cause

The logo text lacks:
1. `whitespace-nowrap` — allowing the browser to break "Yilan Gao" mid-phrase
2. `shrink-0` (i.e., `flex-shrink: 0`) — allowing flex to compress it
3. A codified **priority rule** in the design system that enforces this for all identity-tier elements

---

## Fix

### 1. Locate and fix the Nav component

```tsx
// components/Nav/Nav.tsx  (or wherever your nav lives)

// BEFORE — vulnerable logo node
<Link href="/" className="font-semibold text-lg">
  Yilan Gao
</Link>

// AFTER — identity-protected logo node
<Link
  href="/"
  className="font-semibold text-lg whitespace-nowrap shrink-0"
  // whitespace-nowrap  → never wraps, ever, under any viewport
  // shrink-0           → opts out of flex compression negotiation entirely
>
  Yilan Gao
</Link>
```

The blurb node gets the inverse treatment — it is *allowed* to wrap:

```tsx
// The descriptor line — explicitly permitted to wrap
<p className="text-sm text-neutral-500 min-w-0 shrink">
  Designer, AI systems experience...
</p>
```

`min-w-0` is required here because flex children default to `min-width: auto`, which can paradoxically *prevent* wrapping on the element you actually want to wrap (AP-027).

---

### 2. Codify the rule in the design system token layer

Create a utility class group in your Tailwind config or a dedicated CSS layer that makes the rule declarative and auditable:

```css
/* styles/elan-principles.css  — imported in globals.css */

@layer elan-identity {
  /*
   * PRINCIPLE: Identity Protection (EAP-001)
   *
   * Any element carrying brand identity (logo, nav name, monogram) must:
   *   - Never wrap to a second line
   *   - Never participate in flex-shrink negotiation
   *   - Never be truncated without a deliberate, documented exception
   *
   * Apply `.identity-lock` to all such elements.
   * The descriptor / tagline tier uses `.descriptor-fluid` — it MAY wrap.
   */

  .identity-lock {
    white-space: nowrap;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    overflow: visible;   /* do not clip — if something breaks, let it break visibly */
    min-width: max-content;
  }

  .descriptor-fluid {
    min-width: 0;        /* allows flex to compress and wrap correctly */
    flex-shrink: 1;
    white-space: normal;
  }
}
```

Then in `tailwind.config.ts`, ensure this layer is always included:

```ts
// tailwind.config.ts
import type { Config } from 'tailwindcss'

const config: Config = {
  content: ['./app/**/*.{ts,tsx}', './components/**/*.{ts,tsx}'],
  theme: { extend: {} },
  plugins: [],
  // Elan design system principle: identity-lock and descriptor-fluid
  // are utility classes defined in elan-principles.css and must never
  // be purged — they are identity-tier infrastructure, not page-level styles.
}

export default config
```

---

### 3. Apply the semantic classes in Nav

```tsx
// components/Nav/Nav.tsx — final form

export function Nav() {
  return (
    <nav className="flex items-center gap-4 px-6 py-4">

      {/* IDENTITY TIER — must never wrap, never shrink */}
      <Link href="/" className="identity-lock font-semibold text-lg">
        Yilan Gao
      </Link>

      {/* DESCRIPTOR TIER — may wrap under pressure, that is acceptable */}
      <p className="descriptor-fluid text-sm text-neutral-500">
        Designer, AI systems experience...
      </p>

      {/* nav links etc. */}
    </nav>
  )
}
```

---

## Principle

**EAP-001 — Identity Protection**

> Identity-tier elements (logo, name, monogram) are constitutional — they have zero flexibility budget. They do not shrink, they do not wrap, they do not truncate. If the viewport cannot accommodate them, the *layout around them* must adapt. Descriptor-tier elements (taglines, blurbs, secondary copy) hold the opposite contract: they absorb layout pressure so the identity tier never has to.

This maps to a simple two-tier hierarchy:

| Tier | Class | `flex-shrink` | `white-space` | May wrap? |
|------|-------|--------------|---------------|-----------|
| Identity | `.identity-lock` | `0` | `nowrap` | **Never** |
| Descriptor | `.descriptor-fluid` | `1` | `normal` | **Yes** |

Document this in your Elan design system as a founding constraint, not a preference. Any PR that removes `identity-lock` from a logo or nav name node should fail code review on principle alone.
